Date: 25 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Taiwan CDC 25 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://203.65.72.83/En/dpc/ShowPublication.ASP?RecNo=869>

Taiwan SARS Update 25 Apr 2003
------------------------------
Taiwan CDC announces that people who had been to Hoping Hospital, Taipei
during the period [8-23 Apr 2003?] should have daily temperature checked,
wear masks, and seek immediate medical services should symptoms arise. The
health authorities have adopted the vigorous measures of closing the
hospital and confining all patients and staff members in the hospital for
at least 14 days. Any people who cared for patients in the emergency room
or wards 7A, 7B, and 8B during the period of [8-23 Apr 2003?] are being
quarantined at home.
Taiwan CDC recommends that fix one physician [?] for medical services; as
an alternative, people can call their physician for general consultation;
if they visit a physician, please wear masks.
As of 3:00 PM on 25 Apr 2003, there were 250 possible SARS cases reported:
49 probable, 65 suspected, 89 excluded, and 47 pending cases. Compared with
the previous day, this represents an increase of 8 probable cases. In
accordance with WHO guidelines, 25 of the 49 probable cases and 42 of the
65 suspected cases have been discharged to home quarantine, while the
remaining 24 probable cases and 23 suspected cases are still being cared
for in negative pressure rooms. A total of 138 possible SARS cases have
been discharged from hospitals.
As of 2:00 PM on 25 Apr 2003, a total of 2051 close contacts of probable
SARS cases had been assigned to home quarantine; 1638 of them have
completed their quarantines.
On 24 Apr 2003, 9 incoming passengers and 2 outbound passengers at CKS
International Airport had fever. 3 passengers were referred for medical
evaluation and 2 of them were admitted to hospital. 1 incoming passenger at
Kaohsuing International Airport had fever, but did not require further
medical evaluation.
