[7] Comments
[A]
Date: Fri, 25 Apr 2003 18:38:00 +0800
From: Ding-Ping Liu <dpliu@cdc.gov.tw>
[In response to the comment in the ProMED-mail posting of 24 Apr 2003 (SARS
- worldwide (67): cases 20030424.1007)], the information provided in CDC's
MMWR article [4][B] with the results of current laboratory testing is
curious. According to this article, of the 245 reported combined suspected
and probable cases, 45 (18 per cent) had positive laboratory tests for the
SARS-associated coronavirus; 39 of the 245 (15.9 per cent) had negative
results, 32 suspected and 7 probable cases (7 out of 37 probable cases or
19 per cent) were negative for the SARS associated coronavirus), and 6 of
the probable cases (16 per cent) were reported to have positive tests for
the SARS-associated coronavirus.
We found in this original CDC MMWR article, CDC described the cases as
below: "As of April 23, of the 245 reported SARS cases, 45 (18 per cent)
have diagnostic SARS-CoV laboratory findings (i.e., positive findings based
on detection of antibody to SARS-CoV in serum or evidence of virus in
respiratory specimens by reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction
analysis, or negative findings based on absence of antibody to SARS-CoV in
convalescent serum obtained >21 days after symptom onset)."
It would be more accurate to say that among the 245 reported cases, 45
cases have been laboratory-tested and have conclusive results (positive and
negative). 39 of these 45 lab-tested cases were negative for SARS-CoV, and
only 6 cases of these 45 have been found to have laboratory-confirmed
SARS-CoV infection. Since there are still 24 cases pending final lab
results among the total 37 probable cases, the positive or negative rate is
not yet available. Perhaps we should only say that there are 6 positive and
7 negative among the 13 tested probable cases.
We hope this rephrasing will help your readers understand the whole picture
better. Thank you for your attention.
--
Christine Liu
Center for Disease Control, Taiwan, ROC
<dpliu@cdc.gov.tw>
[B]
Date: Thu, 24 Apr 2003 14:45:07 -0700
From: Stanley Deresinski MC <polishmd@earthlink.net>
In "SARS - worldwide (67): cases, the moderator's interpretation of the CDC
SARS laboratory results are inaccurate. Only 13 "probable" cases have
completed testing: 6 had a positive* result and in 7 the results were
negative**.
*Positive antibody test OR positive PCR.
**No antibody detected in convalescent (>21 days post-symptom onset) serum.
--
Stan Deresinski
<polishmd@earthlink.net>
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[As of 25 Apr 2003 a cumulative total of 4649 probable cases of SARS, with
274 deaths, have been reported to WHO from 27 countries. In the past 24
hours an additional 210 cases have been reported, of which 179 were
reported to have occurred in China and 22 in Hong Kong. China is now
reporting new cases from Beijing, Inner Mongolia, Guangdong , Tianjin,
Hebei, Shanxi, Henan, Guangxi, and Sichuan.
To date, 2206 cases have been reported to have recovered (47.5 per cent),
with outcomes on 2169 (46.7 per cent) of patients still pending. This is
relevant when one starts to calculate the case fatality rate, as outcomes
on almost half of the cases are still pending. The newswires have been
filled with discussions of "increasing case fatality rates," because the
early rates mentioned were less than 4 per cent, and now rates are
approaching 5 per cent. Readers should be reminded that until the outcomes
of all cases are known, and we have a means of determining the numbers of
infected individuals (including those with mild to minimal or no illness),
we will have no "true" denominator to permit an accurate calculation of the
true case fatality rate associated with infection with the SARS-associated
virus.
It is noteworthy that Viet Nam is approaching 2 incubation periods since
the date of onset of the last reported probable case of SARS (30 Apr 2003
will be 20 days since the last case's onset). If no additional cases are
reported, the country will be removed from the affected areas list.
This moderator would like to thank Drs Liu and Deresinski for pointing out
that the correct denominator for numbers of probable SARS cases that have
had laboratory studies completed is 13 (representing 35 per cent of
reported probable SARS patients as of the date of that analysis). Of these
13 probable cases, 7 were negative for the SARS associated coronavirus, and
6 were positive. While this does "increase" the proportion tested that were
positive, these different percentages do not change this moderator's
opinion stated in the 24 Apr 2003 posting: "It appears the verdict is not
yet in on the sensitivity and specificity of currently available tests, or
whether the SARS-associated coronavirus is the "full answer". - Mod.MPP]
